N2  - Criminal statistics for the last few years indicates a certain drop in the number of registered corruption crimes in Russia. A decrease in the number of grave corruption crimes serves as a backdrop for the considerable increase in the number of crimes of small and medium gravity, which is certainly a cause for concern. There is a number of legislative prohibitions aimed at counteracting corruption among civil servants, which can be broken into five groups. The first group of prohibitions was introduced to prevent illegal enrichment of civil servants through the abuse of authority. The second group includes prohibitions aimed at ensuring the constitutional principle of the separation of powers as well as the independence of local authority bodies and trade unions. The third group prohibits public servants from using their official position to serve the interests of other countries, international and foreign organizations, foreign citizens if it contradicts the interests of the Russian state. The fourth group prohibits public servants from using their official position to serve the interests of political parties, other public or religious organizations if it contradicts the interests of their public office. The fifth group encompasses prohibitions aimed at ensuring that public servants observe the rules of public behavior and dissemination of classified information. Thus there is a rather wide circle of legislative limitations for public servants. At the same time, the efficiency of their implementation is so low that the law enforcement issues cannot be overlooked. The declared principle of unavoidability of liability for public servants committing corruption crimes remains but a declaration in a number of cases. The fuzziness of procedural norms and the absence of effective organizational mechanisms for punishing offenders sometimes prevent the enforcement this principle, which practically nullifies the benefit of including in the law a vast number of prohibitions aimed at counteracting corruption. All this certainly reduces the effectiveness of counteracting corruption among public servants and shows that there is an urgent necessity for a further improvement of anti-corruption legislation and the practice of its enforcement.
