N2  - Although the relationship between Russian government and society in the nineteenth century is often portrayed in terms of conflict, cooperation was more typically the rule. The tsarist state encouraged, sanctioned and patronized private associations dedicated to the pursuit of national betterment and the prestige of the realm. The interests of state and society appeared to be shared interests, and on many projects monarchy and officialdom were willing to collaborate with private individuals. However, the increasing civic activism of private associations during the second half of the nineteenth century challenged the authorities' ability to control the public sphere, and the relationship between state and society turned gradually from cooperation to conflict. We may chart the trajectory from cooperation to confrontation by examining the Free Economic Society's involvement in education. Although the government bureaucracy, the zemstvos, and teachers' professional organizations have received the attention of historians, less is known about the work of Russia's science societies. The involvement of private associations in popular education during the second half of the nineteenth century demonstrates the opportunities, as well as the limitations, of nongovernmental public action. An examination of a division of the Free Economic Society known as the Literacy Committee will also provide a case study of the interaction between officialdom, an association, and the broader public as well as an example of the horizontal linkages in society that associations facilitated. The initial partnership between state and society turned into conflict, as the Literacy Committee spearheaded a rise in public activity in the 1890s. This civic activism, as well as the claim of the Literacy Committee's leaders to a voice in public policy, raised the specter of a vast archipelago of unauthorized and unscrutinized public initiative in education; conflict more and more entered into the relationship between government and society. By operating in a legally sanctioned public sphere and by mobilizing a public, the Literacy Committee, along with other education associations, the zemstvos and the city councils, were a lever used by activists in an attempt to wrest education from government tutelage. However constrained by the government, participation in nongovernmental associations gave the public a voice and allowed activists to challenge government tutelage. Using the vehicle of the association, Russian education activists framed public opinion, organized public meetings around issues of concern, and claimed an advocacy role in public policy.
