N2  - The contestability of delegated government actions remains one of the bedrock questions of administrative law. In what sense are policies and decisions that may ultimately reflect the will of the elective branches of American government, but that are necessarily given to administrative officials, subject to challenge by those affected, or even by those who are not? In the wake of the Administrative Procedures Act (APA) of 1946, an entire literature and subdiscipline of law has arisen, seeking to define the appropriate bounds of administrative discretion and to identify those institutions – whether in APA-related procedures of notice-and-comment rulemaking or in cost–benefit analysis of proposed rules coupled with unitary executive review – that best constrain this discretion while preserving socially beneficial public policies. No self-respecting law school neglects to fill out a roster of administrative law teachers and scholars, and there remain many applied fields of law (food and drug law, communications law, environmental law) in which the institutions and precepts of American administrative law figure critically in teaching and scholarship. Political scientists and other social scientists have, finally, rendered their own contributions to the field of administrative law. These contributions came in several waves, not least in the sober reminders of scholars that the APA and its institutions could be used for political control over the bureaucratic state, that rulemaking institutions attract special interest pressure, and, most recently, that executive regulatory review itself is an important site of lobbying. Institutions that constrain the administrative state open themselves yet more venues for special interest influence. To this day, however, a prominent and occasionally influential practice of contestation – the petition to an administrative agency – has largely escaped the administrative lawyer’s notice. The collective ignorance of the administrative petition appears especially puzzling, given the frequent use of these institutions by businesses, consumer groups, law firms, and other entities in American political economy. The rulemaking petitions with which administrative lawyers are familiar today compose just the tendril legacy of a much richer pattern of supplicating administrative officials and organizations, a pattern that goes back centuries.
