significant national differences, Europe's postwar model of democracy
was based on a number of key characteristics: the reassertion of the
authority of the nation-state and of directly-elected parliaments as
well as a culture of coalition government which accorded considerable
freedom of manoeuvre to the central bureaucracy and to paragovernmental
lobbyists at the expense of direct popular participation. This article
