idies include, but are not limited to, substantial tax deductions for employer health insurance, hospital and nursing home construction, health workforce (mainly Medicare physicians) training, research (e. g., National Institutes of Health), and tax exemptions for nonprofits. The latest data for 2007 show that the largest tax subsidy for private health insurance-the federal exclusion from income and payroll taxes of employer and employee contributions for employer-sponsored health insurance-is estimated at $200 billion in lost revenues (Kaiser Family Foundation [KFF], 2008). The Joint Committee on Taxation (2008) reports an even higher amount: $143 billion lost in federal income tax and $100 billion for FICA taxes as tax expenditures for the employer coverage tax exclusion. In 2003, legislation continued and expanded government funding for proprietary healthcare (e. g., the pharmaceutical industry's Medicare Part D bill) that prohibits Medicare from negotiating drug prices and excludes Medicare from participating in or competing with private drug management companies, and forbids drug discounts to those eligible for both Medicare and Medicaid (dual eligibles), while giving bonus subsidies to private Medicare Advantage plans. The 2010 ACA both reduced and added different and new government subsidies for mostly private (and largely for-profit) Medicare services. Although the ACA cut or reduced some government subsidies (e. g., managed care and provider payments), industry lobbying has scaled back or delayed many such cost-saving provisions.
