working in the cotton mills of Chongqing, the Nationalist wartime
capital. Upon joining the workforce in the late 1930s, most cotton mill
hands were young, uneducated women expected to endure hard work and
remain physically confined to the factories. By 1945, women workers were
at the forefront of a militant labour movement, writing manifestoes and
petitioning government officials. This process of politicization stemmed
from their decision to work in factories, which breached societal norms,
and their experience of disciplined labour regimes and brutal working
conditions, which fostered an incipient class-consciousness. Moreover,
