Extant research offers explanations based on institutional arrangements
and external shocks (e.g. political or economic crises). We go beyond
such system-level variables to argue that the characteristics of
ministerial appointees are a function of the portfolio they are being
appointed to. Drawing on theories of political delegation, we argue that
outsider and expert appointments to ministerial office are affected by a
portfolio's policy jurisdiction, its financial resources and appointment
powers, and the partisan leanings of the ministerial bureaucracy. We
