ancy arises in the High Court there is the usual speculation about the identity of the person likely to be appointed to fill the vacancy. At both federal and state levels, judicial appointments are in reality made by the government of the day. In formal constitutional terms, the appointment of federal judges is made by the Governor-General in Council, while the appointment of state judges is made by the Governor in Council. A discussion paper issued by the federal Attorney-General’s Department in 1993 succinctly describes the appointment process as varying according to the ‘personal preferences of individual Attorneys-General’.
