N2  - One global reality raises serious questions. Despite all the international undertakings, some 2.1 billion people (i.e. around 30 per cent of the world’s population) drink “dangerous” water that presents health risks.1 In consequence, managing to supply everyone with this essential good is not just a matter of friendly discussion between specialists, but challenges the foundations of collective action and water policies. How do we explain why, in a world where billions of dollars are invested in the entertainment or armament industries, it is not possible to develop (and finance) programmes that will bring improvements to countries where this essential good is lacking? A central hypothesis of this book is that in order to understand the problems of the water sector, the obstacles preventing its proper functioning and the inequalities that arise from them, we need to move away from debates about the legal status of the water operators - public versus private - and consider their actual practices. What do the protagonists of the water sector actually do? What actions do they undertake? Under what institutional arrangements? Both economic history and research on firms show that some companies are driven by profit, but others innovate and bring progress for a “fair” return. There may be public bureaucracies overstaffed due to patronage and clientilist practices, but also public enterprises that are competent and efficient. Ultimately, the results are explained by internal properties (professionalism) and the capacity of the protagonists to establish institutions that provide incentives and points of equilibrium between the interests concerned. In other words, one needs to focus on the practices, the frameworks in which they are embedded and the conditions of their implementation. In order to develop this line of research, we begin with two cases which, in many respects, stand at the antipodes of economic doxa: the Chongqing joint venture and the Salt River Project 