N2  - Since the late 1990s, Japan’s legal system has changed as a result of changes in Japan’s economy and society as well as reforms to the postwar legal order, including changes to the system of legal training and to criminal trials. These changes have the potential to “democratize” Japanese law, in the sense that democratization is an ongoing process of broadening public participation and bringing the state into a greater degree of consultation with the society it governs.1 Lawmakers, jurists, and interest groups have attempted to democratize the law by expanding the bar, increasing lay participation in criminal legal processes, and giving more scope to public intervention in administrative decision making. Changes to Japan’s legal system have been incremental, and the reforms limited, but law, legal practitioners, and courts have the potential to play a larger role in Japanese society in the coming decade than they did during Japan’s postwar democratization and era of rapid economic growth. Law and courts are essential to the modern state. They enable the state to exercise control over society, resolve disputes between individuals, and fill in the gaps in rules made by legislators (Shapiro 1981: 1-8). A system of law that is autonomous and transparent also reassures investors and enhances the stature of a modernizing regime like Meiji Japan or reform-era China. The Meiji regime made the adoption of a European-style legal system a priority precisely because such a system was integral to ending the unequal treaty system and its extraterritoriality provisions (Haley 1991: 67ff). Japan’s post-Second World War Occupation overlaid rights guarantees drawn from U.S. sources onto legal structures and ideas imported from the civil law systems of France and Germany.2 The tension between Continental (civil law) and Anglo-American (common law) approaches to legal problems goes back to the beginning of the modern Japanese state and lives on today in the debate over how to structure legal education and administrative law (Miyazawa et al. 2008; Uga 2007). The contemporary Japanese legal system reflects this diverse intellectual heritage in its combination of code-based jurisprudence with a system of courts of general jurisdiction that enjoy broad powers of administrative and constitutional review. Despite the wide-ranging review power of courts and the rights-centered postwar constitution, Japan’s legal institutions play less of a role in politics than do law and courts in the Anglo-American tradition and are more comparable to courts in European democracies. One explanation for the relatively small role of courts and formal legal contestation is a cultural one: Japanese people prefer to resolve disputes through mediation and face social disapproval for engaging in formal disputing (Kawashima 1963). A second explanation is a rebuttal to the cultural explanation, and holds that the apparent preference for informal resolution of disputes is really a result of institutional incapacity. Japanese people may accept courts but find that resolving disputes through formal mechanisms is more costly (especially in terms of time) than resolving them through informal mechanisms (Haley 1978), and so their selection of alternative mechanisms for resolving disputes represents a rational evaluation of costs and benefits of disputing, as in other systems (Ramseyer and Nakazato 1999). In addition, political influence over Japanese courts may make them less powerful than their review powers suggest (Ramseyer and Rasmusen 1997; Law 2009). Japanese courts have played an important role in politics, though, to the extent that litigation helped frame, and put on the political agenda, issues such as employment rights for women, social discrimination, and pollution (Upham 1987). The sections that follow describe how some key institutions-the courts, the bar, the criminal justice system, and the bureaucracy-have functioned in the postwar political order and examine how the reforms to those institutions may serve to democratize them. These reforms include an expansion of the bar, the addition of professional law school to the official legal training process, the introduction of a lay assessor system for trying serious crimes, and information disclosure rules. At this point, the democratization is more potential than actual, and more public participation and access do not mean that Japan’s legal system will become more fair or more humane. Rather than serving the interests of justice, participation and access could make the legal system more punitive, more unpredictable, and more expensive (Kagan 2001).
