ernal congressional rules with respect to the acceptance of gifts and travel by Members of Congress and staff from certain outside private interests, such as lobbyists and their clients. Amendments to the Lobbying Disclosure Act of 1995, and to internal House and Senate rules, were made in S. 1, passed by the House on July 31, 2007, and by the Senate on August 2, 2007, and signed into law, P.L. 110-81, on September 14, 2007.1 Additionally, changes to the internal rules of the House were made previously by H.Res. 6, 110th Congress, adopted by the House on January 4, 2007.2 © 2010 Nova Science Publishers, Inc.
