N2  - Introduction France has undergone important changes over the past two decades. But these changes are far from being unambiguous. In 1987, Yves Mény insisted that, despite being commonly considered as “the prototype of centralization” (1987: 88), the French system of relations between centre and periphery has always been more complex than commonly thought. Two aspects were particularly underscored: first, the strong presence of the “local” at the central level and the persistence of “localist” values in the French political culture; and second, the ability of local actors to tame central influence in daily negotiations on public policy implementation (Grémion 1976). Socio-historical researches (Politix 2001) have shown that the birth of the republican regime in late-nineteenth-century France did not simply involve the imposition of new rules by the centre on peripheries. Rather, the consolidation of the regime was the result of the colonisation of the centre by local republican “notables” and “petites patries” (Chanet 1996), with the commune seen as the cradle of republican values. The later reinforcement of the central state and of ministerial bureaucracies, especially with the creation of the Fifth Republic in 1958, never really marginalised local actors in central and local policy-making processes (Tarrow 1977). Paradoxically, the impression of a strong centralisation was also due to the Jacobinism of local politicians, and especially of mayors, who considered the local interest a mere reflection of the general interest defined centrally (Borraz 1998), which they helped forge thanks to the multiple officeholding system. But these same politicians who helped reinforce central state legitimacy were also actively trying to preserve local interests. Thus, the functioning of the French local political system was so far from the stereotype of a highly centralised country that the relevance of the centreperiphery framework was increasingly questioned even before the Decentralisation Acts of the early 1980s. Recent developments allow ambiguity to persist. It is tempting to suggest that two waves of decentralisation (1982-1983 and 2004), the assault of globalisation and EU institutionalisation on the central state, and the localisation of economic interactions (Balme 1996) have definitively made the local government level the more vivid, legitimate, efficient and influential scale of government, along with the regions, at the expense of départements and the central national state. The actual situation is more complicated, for three main reasons. First, the fate of the different levels constituting the three-tier system of French local government (communes, départements, regions) is determined both by deep economic and social change, and - perhaps mainly - by political inflexions and strategies at the central level (Pinson and Le Galès 2005). From this perspective, the French central state’s strategy for territorial reorganisation and decentralisation has fluctuated considerably during the past two decades, owing to political and ideological change or to opportunistic considerations. Second, the trend of territorial reorganisation is unclear, because in a three-tier system in which none of the three components exerts a form of tutelage over the others, each tier is tempted to play its own cards in the reorganisation process, which is a competitive game with uncertain outcomes and which potentially differs from one local or regional situation to another. Outcomes are even more uncertain when the central state’s “favourites” change from one election to another. Twenty-five years after the first Decentralisation Acts, it is no easier to say which level has won the great game of political authority redistribution than it was in 1987 (Fontaine 2007; Zeller 2006). Third, this great difference in the balance between different levels of local or regional bodies is reinforced by the fact that at each individual level, and particularly at the municipal level, the past two decades reveal a powerful process of internal differentiation. There have always been differences between a small rural commune with a population of less than 100 and one with a million inhabitants, despite the fact that French law makes no distinction between them. But there were also similarities. In both cases the capacity to address problems largely depended on access to central government resources, programmes and funds. In both cases the mayor was a key person whose capacity to act was linked to his ability to mobilise political connections to obtain resources. Vertical relationships were more important than horizontal networking, owing to the concentration of resources at the centre. This situation has changed radically, but it still varies considerably between places. In large, thriving cities, a pluralist political landscape has emerged, resources are dispersed and state field services are no longer the dominant actors (Pinson 2006). These pluralist situations require intergovernmental arrangements (Goldsmith 2004), among which inter-municipal institutions are the prominent feature. These arrangements have changed political styles and relationships, helping the rise of a capacity for metropolitan collective action. Elsewhere, in rural areas, in declining medium-sized towns, inter-municipal cooperation is much more difficult, since each individual commune is tempted to put itself under the patronage of a superior tier, the département or the state. Mény (1987: 90) noted that the appearance and deepening of an urban-rural cleavage was one of the clearest features in the evolution of French territorial organisation between 1945 and 1985. By 2007, with the rise of influential collective powers (“pouvoirs d’agglomération”) in big cities, the landscape of communal power had become even more varied and increasingly differentiated. © 2010 Michael J. Goldsmith and Edward C. Page for selection and editorial matter; individual contributors their contribution.
