N2  - Toward the end of The Shield's (FX, 2002-2008) second season, the writers of the series make the unusual move of inserting in medias res an episode that operates as a kind of prequel to the entire narrative covered by the show. This episode, titled "Co-pilot" (2.9), encompasses events immediately anterior to those presented in the original series pilot. Its foci are Assistant Chief Ben Gilroy's establishment of the satellite police precinct in Farmington, the appointment and arrival of some of the precinct's key figures, and the initial development of collegial rivalries and loyalties at the Barn. Most significant perhaps, the copilot tells the story of how the Strike Team came into being: it relates both the official establishment of the detail itself and the first, unofficial emergence of the unethical practices that will rapidly come to define its modus operandi. Corruption and brutality are not, it turns out, tactics toward which Mackey is somehow constitutionally disposed (we even witness him restrain Curtis Lemansky when he becomes too physical with one suspect), but to which, under certain institutional pressures, he has quickly grown habituated. This is made clear within the copilot in Mackey's management of the Strike Team's first case, the drive-by murder of two prostitutes. Here the team members are faced with knowing that their suspect, a dealer and pimp named Lionel Phipps, is guilty and yet being unable to ascertain his guilt formally within the limits of the law. Under pressure from both Gilroy and Captain David Aceveda to get immediate results, Mackey is reluctantly led to find a "shortcut." Planting crack in Phipps's apartment and blackmailing an associate of Phipps's to swear to its presence, Mackey obtains probable cause for searching the home of this otherwise untouchable suspect and gets his man. Significant in this particular narrative is the way in which the Strike Team's inaugural case is initially figured by those who secretly engineer it as exceptional. The decision to deploy blackmail and plant evidence is not made arbitrarily or casually but is impelled by a necessity specific to the case (there is no means at hand within the law for arresting the man who has broken the law) and to the immediate institutional pressures within the juridical system under which it has to be handled (the "bosses'" imperatives must be met). Thus, Mackey-with heavy dramatic irony apparent to anyone who has watched previous episodes- reassures his men by insisting that Phipps is a regrettable "one off": "Once we get our feet on solid ground, get a couple of wins under our belt, we go back to doing it the right way. We need this. Just this once" (emphasis added). Toward the end of the episode, however, there is a short but meaningful exchange between Mackey and his colleague Shane Vendrell. Vendrell takes him aside and informs him that he has spoken to the other Strike Team members about what happened with Phipps earlier in the day: vendrell: I talked to both of them, and they're cool about what went down. mackey: Good. vendrell: We got Lionel . . . mackey: Yeah. It was easy, wasn't it? vendrell: Yeah. A little too easy. With the cameras focused intensely on the two detectives' knowing smiles and with the viewer's knowledge of subsequent events, it is thus made clear-with great economy and understatement-that in "Co-pilot" we are witnessing the moment in which the supposed exceptionality of the Strike Team's inaugural case becomes tacitly structured into the very operation of the team's normal functioning. What is essential to stress here is the importance of chronology. The exchange is framed so as to emphasize its causal anteriority to the event that commentators endlessly describe as Mackey's "original sin"-the murder of Aceveda's late addition to the Strike Team, Terry Crowley.1 The exchange between Vendrell and Mackey significantly takes place just as the latter is leaving the Barn to meet Crowley for the first time and bring him back to introduce to the team. We know from the original series pilot that Mackey will murder Crowley because Crowley has been tasked with covertly investigating Strike Team corruption. What we witness in "Copilot," then, is not just the one and only manifestation of the Strike Team before the addition of Crowley, but the foundational establishment of the ethos within the team that will make Crowley's murder inevitable. My point in underscoring this sequence of events is that "Co-pilot" introduces into The Shield and into the story of Mackey's violent itinerary an element that is, in effect, even more originary than the putative "original sin": namely, the narrative of how exception has become the rule. It is true that Crowley's murder is akin to what in dramatic tragedy would be referred to as the pro-tarchos ate- (primal crime):2 it haunts Mackey's entire career and constitutes the most significant and dramatic portion of his eventual confession in season 7. But what "Co-pilot" introduces and articulates is the determination of a critical foundation to which even that "primal" transgression is secondary. Everything in Mackey's and the Strike Team's professional trajectory depends on this dramatically understated yet constitutive moment. The truly originary event in the Strike Team's history is precisely this tacit movement whereby an emergency measure, undertaken with the initial aim of "doing it the right way" in future, becomes in effect the essential paradigm for future engagement. This essay teases out the critical stakes of the Strike Team's foundational narrative in order to offer an analysis of the "politics of exception" in The Shield. Drawing on the work of Italian philosopher Giorgio Agamben, I situate the imbrication between the show's thematic preoccupation with exceptional juridical measures and the particular cultural and political climate in which the show emerged. Agamben's account of the politics of exception, I suggest, offers a critical framework from within which we can both grasp the conceptual determinations that lie behind the rapid drama of Mackey's policing and begin to interrogate the problematic ideological investments that the representation of his policing evinces. I go on to track the ways in which the series habitually frames and structures Mackey's professional deployment of extralegal tactics in order to propose that in spite of the apparent negations articulated within the series, The Shield retains a fundamental structural complicity with Mackey and with the mode of sovereign power he embodies. Copyright © 2012 by Syracuse University Press.
