N2  - Much has been made of the `imperial' influence of international actors
(Chopra 2000) and their view of Timor-Leste as a petri dish for
post-conflict development. However, this view obscures the ways in which
conflict-era actors and their networks shape core decision regarding
resource allocation. This article examines the political economies of
resistance-era networks in the post-conflict period, focusing
specifically on the large-scale pensions programme. The article argues
that these former fighters tasked with registration verification serve
as `street level bureaucrats' and have re-shaped the programme to
