N2  - Introduction Civic engagement and community development programs provide a unique opportunity for underrepresented communities to participate in the governance process of their country. For this reason, researchers and practitioners have begun to explore the intersection between civic engagement and community development. Equally, there is also the question of the role of citizenship in demanding better governance through civic engagement and community development. This chapter focuses on how civic engagement shapes community development by focusing on the role of citizenship using The Gambia as a case study. Government officials, Civil Society Organizations (CSOs) and Community-Based Organizations (CBOs) were surveyed on the level of civic engagement of citizens and whether these translated into meaningful community development activities and/or transformation in community policies. The political landscape of many African countries is changing and The Gambia is no exception to that. As a byproduct of a call for better governance in recent years from tyrants, dictators, and presidents for life, many African countries, including The Gambia, have witnessed an increase in citizens taking an active role in the political process. Although gains have been made in the development of stable political systems in many countries in Sub Saharan Africa, recent incidents in the Ivory Coast, Mali, and The Gambia, where respective presidents have historically rejected the results of elections and the will of the people, suggest that there are still democratic issues to be resolved. However, despite these situations, citizens are taking an active role in the political process to oust dictators by facing their fears. To strengthen and amalgamate the gains made by citizens in The Gambia, it is important that these gains be reinforced by CBOs and civil societies against misrule. While there are no disagreements on the existence of civil societies in Africa or in The Gambia by scholars, the study of civil society is however plagued with definitional muddiness. There seem to be disagreements on actors and groups that constitute civil society. For this chapter, we chose to use the definition provided by the London School of Economics (LSE): Civil society refers to the arena of uncoerced collective action around shared interests, purposes and values. In theory, its institutional forms are distinct from those of the state, family and market, though in practice, the boundaries between state, civil society, family and market are often complex, blurred and negotiated. Civil society commonly embraces a diversity of spaces, actors and institutional forms, varying in their degree of formality, autonomy and power. Civil societies are often populated by organizations such as registered charities, development nongovernmental organizations, community groups, youth and women’s organizations, faith-based organizations, professional associations, trade unions, self-help groups, social movements, business associations, coalitions, farmer associations and advocacy groups. © 2018 Taylor & Francis.
