N2  - Introduction Since the political revolution in 1932, the political party system in Thailand has developed incrementally, but internal party structures and local branch systems have not appeared as successful means to consolidate party structures. The absence of party rootedness in local constituencies has frequently resulted in the demise of parties. Although many major Thai political parties such as the New Aspiration Party (NAP), the Phalang Dharma Party (PDP) and the Democrat Party (DP) have claimed that they have established genuine local branches, those branches were set up primarily to benefit individual party leaders and to create the image of a mass-based party (King 1997: 23-5; Ockey 1994: 273 and Askew 2008: 327). Unlike party branches in more developed democracies such as those of Western Europe, many branches in Thailand, particularly those belonging to small parties, did not function effectively as local party units. They did not attempt to recruit more members or forge stronger party affiliation among party members. Nor did they routinely organize political activities at the local level or provide resources to support the party during elections. These weaknesses limit the role of local branches in voter mobilization. And yet, even though these local branches do not function effectively in politics, their numbers mushroom. What are the reasons behind those branch establishments? This chapter aims to examine the main factors that have contributed to the rapid formation of local branches across Thailand in order to understand the structural relationship between the party center and their local organizations. The analysis focuses on parties’ incentives for the formation of branches. I address the question of why party leaders have decided to establish a great number of local branches across the country even though it is usually deemed more effective to utilize their own personal networks to mobilize voters in elections (Darling 1971; Callahan and McCargo 1996; McCargo 1997; Ockey 2003). I pay specific attention to the DP’s branch promotion policy due to the rapidly increasing number of DP branches over time. This large number of DP branches distinguishes the party from other major political parties in Thai politics. As can be seen in Table 9.1, the DP has contributed a relatively large amount of human and material resources to the advancement of its branch promotion policy. During the early years after its formation in 1946, the DP only set up 11 branches, but by 2008 the local branch numbers had increased to 196 branches across the country.1 Most local branches had been disbanded together with their party during the military regimes. After the reemergence of democratic government, political parties, including the DP, reorganized their branches. In the past, the local party branch system was not widely developed by political parties. Scholars of Thai politics such as Kramol Thongthammachart (1966), Kachatpai Burutphat (1968), James Ockey (1994), Duncan McCargo (1997) and Pricha Hongkrilert (1981) have argued that Thai parties are dominated by professional politicians and technocrats, tend to be controlled by individual leaders, are subsidized by powerful figures or interest groups, and have no clear policy platforms. These characteristics of Thai parties left little room for the development of strong party organizations with large memberships and effectively developed local branch systems. Rather, this weak organizational structure led to the prevalence of clientelistic networks in which hua khanaen, or voting chiefs, play a key role. In order to win an election, candidates rely on their personal networks and the hua khanaen who are able to convince voters to elect a particular candidate in return for money (Ockey 2000: 83-5). These hua khanaen, including village headmen, factory owners and retired government officers, establish tightly knit relationships with party candidates. Their activities are generally limited to one or two villages. They support party candidates to conduct electoral campaigns and in many cases they help with channeling candidates’ financial resources to voters. It is not enough for candidates to spend money on vote-buying; it is also vital for hua khanaen to direct that money through the right channels.2 There are many reports of candidates spending large amounts of money, but failing to win elections as a result of having chosen the wrong hua khanaen. The close connection between candidates and hua khanaen is, therefore, essential in order to ensure the electoral victory of individual candidates. At the same time, these relationships foster the clientelistic networks between candidates and their hua khanaen. The prominence of clientelistic networks has made parties and their leaders reluctant to develop strong local branches as a tool for voter mobilization in elections. Candidates and parties tended to use the old style system in order to garner their votes in elections. Hence, local branches were only marginally important in the eyes of politicians and party leaders. Back in the 1980s, major parties such as NAP and PDP claimed to have established local branches as a means to build mass-based organizations, but those branches were not formally registered with the Ministry of Interior (MOI) at that time. In fact, many of those branches tended to serve as private offices of individual Members of Parliament, and only later were claimed as local party branches. They were not established by the party center. Instead, it was the party MPs who funded their establishment and administrative affairs (McCargo 1993: 20; King 1996: 56). Subsidies allotted by MPs frequently allowed those MPs to control these branches. Several branch officers were also the MP’s vote canvasser. Subsequently, these branches tended to garner support for MPs rather than cultivating votes for the party organization. The clientelistic networks between branch members and MPs weakened the political party affiliation among branch members. More importantly, this relationship often resulted in the decline of those branches if MPs defected from the party. The significance of party branches, however, was widely discussed again after the promulgation of the 1997 Constitution and the 1998 Political Party Act. Numerous local party branches were established by small and large political parties. This increasing number of branches was partly a result of the requirement of branch formation in the Party Act (see Section 29, the 1998 Political Party Act) and the promulgation of the Political Party Development Fund (PDF) - state subsidies for the development of political parties and branches - in the 1998 Political Party Act (Kris Aungwong 2004). Major parties at that time, such as the Thai Rak Thai (TRT) Party and the Thai Nation Party (TNP), set up new branches during this period, if only to fulfill the bare minimum of the formal requirements.3 Moreover, numerous smaller and less affluent parties established local branches in order to maximize their share from the PDF (Krit Auewong, 2005). Many small parties set up more than one branch per constituency and a large number of small parties controlled more than 100 branches across the nation. As shown in Figure 9.1, more than 1, 000 branches were established after the promulgations of the 1998 Political Party Act and the PDF. In 2001, there were 1, 611 branches, approximately 900 branches more than in 1999. The number of new branches kept rising until 2004. By 2005, however, the branch numbers declined again due to stricter Election Commission regulations on branch formation and the revision of the monetary allocation formula. According to the new regulations written in 2004, political parties can no longer include all their branches in calculations for final state subsidies. Only branches that passed the evaluation criteria of the Election Commission can be included in the allocation formula to calculate the final total of state subsidies. In 2009, only six of 36 political parties received state subsidies due to their branch numbers. The PDF, therefore, was an important stimulus for the rapid expansion of local branches after the promulgation of the 1998 Political Party Act. While the PDF encouraged small parties to set up local branches, it is less clear whether these state subsidies also influenced the formation of branches in the larger parties such as the DP. In this chapter, I emphasize that the PDF was indeed important, but it was only one of three underlying significant factors that contributed to a previously unexplained increase in the number of local party branches in the DP. The other two factors are the party’s intention to expand its rootedness at local level and intra-party competition. In the following paragraphs I will analyze these factors and their effects on the DP’s branch promotion policy. Moreover, I will make comparisons with two other major political parties, the Thai Rak Thai Party (now reincarnated as the Pheu Thai Party) and the Thai Nation Party (now known as the Thai Nation Development Party). I underscore the implications of these three factors for the weakness of party organization and the existence of clientelistic networks within the party organization. I will conclude that with the exception of branches in the south and in Bangkok, many DP branches do not function effectively as party offices at the constituency level. Many DP branches were set up for other purposes - representing the mass party image, securing the power of individual leaders within the party and maximizing the party’s share of state subsidies - instead of promoting the party’s rootedness at the local level. © 2013 selection and editorial material, Dirk Tomsa and Andreas Ufen.
