N2  - After years spent trying, and failing, to prevent paediatric tobacco use in the face of an industry that was spending billions of dollars to promote its products, public policy emerged as an alternative tool for changing attitudes to tobacco. Shaping public policy decisions requires skills which can be taught and learned. First, it is important to identify the level of government to be influenced. The four main targets are elected federal, state, or local government officials, and non-elected administrative rule makers at all levels; in general, the further away and the higher the level, the harder they are to influence. Many people find it difficult to make a substantial difference at the federal level but their ability increases dramatically with state government. City or county officials are the most accessible level of government and are the easiest for a genuine grass roots effect. To initiate policy change, it is necessary to select activities that will attract support (e.g. reducing children's access to tobacco, restricting tobacco advertising, promoting clean air), to gather likely allies from the community (e.g. medical associations, volunteer health organizations, parent-teacher-student associations) and to approach sympathetic legislators, representatives and officials. It is equally important to know the extent of the opposition and, in particular, the tactics of the tobacco industry. However, times have changed, and where once policy makers only heard from tobacco industry lobbyists they now have constituents asking questions about their voting record on matters that affect us all.
