N2  - INTRODUCTION As I wait outside the office of a senior bureaucrat of the Finance Ministry of the Indian government in Delhi, I notice two impeccably dressed gentlemen waiting for him. Requesting them to wait even longer, the bureaucrat allows me into his office, and I silently thank my university affiliation and good luck for the priority I receive. After ushering me in, the bureaucrat volunteers that the people waiting outside are senior-level associates with a prominent Delhi-based corporate law firm. They had sought a meeting with him to justify why the private security agency that one of their foreign clients proposes to start in India deserved exemption from the protracted approval process that would otherwise have to be followed under the Indian foreign investment laws. If they succeed in making a case for exemption, it may well be a precedent for other foreign investors proposing to invest in a similar business format in future.This experience perhaps best describes the subject of this chapter by illustrating one of the many ways in which corporate law firms are influencing the country’s policy frameworks. Worldwide, scholars and the general population traditionally perceive the lawyer as an inherently political actor (Dezalay and Garth 2010; Krishnan 2013). Successful legal professionals often have relationships with government officials and political connections (Krishnan 2013). Although the Indian legal profession has been widely acclaimed for leading sociopolitical movements during the country’s Independence era, it has since been perceived as largely aloof from policy advocacy, having been accused of restricting its advocacy role to courtrooms (Galanter 1989; Krishnan 2003). The litigating bar is often applauded for limited policy outcomes achieved through public interest litigation (PIL) (Anant and Singh 2002; Krishnan 2003, 100; Perry-Kessaris 2008). The government also regularly consults senior lawyers, most notably the attorney general and the solicitor general, on proposed legislation.As documented in the Overview of this volume, until very recently the corporate bar constituted a small segment of the Indian legal profession. Moreover, it has been frequently criticized for its lethargy in policy activism (Krishnan 2010). The influence on law and policy of Washington law firms in the United States and Magic Circle firms in the United Kingdom and the eurozone has been extensively documented by the academia and media. © Cambridge University Press 2017.
